content:
Well, the contract is very limited what can be checked within the EVM:

```
        // Extended ABI length checks since dynamic types are used.
        require(pubkey.length == 48, "DepositContract: invalid pubkey length");
        require(withdrawal_credentials.length == 32, "DepositContract: invalid withdrawal_credentials length");
        require(signature.length == 96, "DepositContract: invalid signature length");

        // Check deposit amount
        require(msg.value >= 1 ether, "DepositContract: deposit value too low");
        require(msg.value % 1 gwei == 0, "DepositContract: deposit value not multiple of gwei");
        uint deposit_amount = msg.value / 1 gwei;
        require(deposit_amount <= type(uint64).max, "DepositContract: deposit value too high");
```

So, it basically does sanity checks:
1. lenght checks on the input data
2. value checks on the deposit amounts
3. further check on deposit data roots

On the testnets we often had invalid deposits. That was caused by either outdated or misconfigured tooling. An invalid deposit is a deposit that _went through_ the checks in the contract but still contains an invalid BLS signature.

I created a tracking ticket https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/issues/2081

On the testnets we basically just used it to investigate why there would be invalid signatures, identified the issue and fixed the tooling. This is probably fine if we can ensure that all our tooling is battle-tested for a mainnet launch.

But then again, we saw invalid deposits for _every_ testnet launch. Now that we are nearing a mainnet launch, we should tripple-check that this will not happen. 

Back in spring I was hoping we will get the precompile before mainnet launch, eventually allowing us to do signature checks in the contract itself, rejecting formally correct deposits with invalid signatures. That would futher prevent accidentally "burning" mainnet ether.
